omical essays, Byron’s cannibals and other deviant diners, and Kantian nausea, Taste resituates Romanticism as a period that naturally saw the rise of the restaurant and the pleasures of the table as a cultural field for the practice of aesthetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAesthetics, British. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aFood habits in literature. 0aFood in literature. 0aGastronomy in literature. 0aTaste in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030010652740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030013305940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133059423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300133059/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY